{
  "doc_id": "57992",
  "text": "Within this context, we focused on resolving the mechanisms and evolutionary forces that lead to the common haplotypes that carry the deletion of the glutathione S-transferase mu 1 (GSTM1) gene in humans ( Figure 1A ). GSTM1 is a member of the GST gene family, which code for cellular detoxifying enzymes and studied intensively within cancer biology and pharmacogenomics context [CITATION_1] . However, these enzymes are functionally relevant to human evolution as well. It has already been shown that they contribute to cellular detoxification of naturally existing products [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . For example, GST enzymes metabolize sulforaphane, which is an abundant product in cruciferous vegetables with unknown metabolic effects [CITATION_4] . Similarly, they metabolize prostaglandin, an important naturally existing metabolite and a target of aspirin (Ricciotti and FitzGerald 2011) . Prostaglandin affects multiple evolutionarily relevant processes, including constriction of the blood vessels and platelet aggregation. As such, it is plausible that variation affecting GST gene family may have adaptive effects. In fact, such adaptive evolution in humans has been documented for variation affecting other metabolizing genes. These examples include but not limited to the deletion of the UDP Glucuronosyltransferase Family 2 Member B17 (UGT2B17) [CITATION_5] , and single nucleotide variation affecting other metabolizing genes, such as N-acetyltransferase 2 (NAT2) [CITATION_6] , alcohol dehydrogenase [CITATION_7] , and Glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD) [CITATION_8] . Therefore, it is not a stretch to imagine that the members of the metabolizing functions of GST gene family are adaptively relevant. Within that context, the deletion of GSTM1 and other variants in this locus may have a broader effect on the neighboring GSTM gene family, members of which have similar metabolizing functions [CITATION_9] .",
